1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,940
For this demo, I'd like to introduce you to Beautiful Soup,

2
00:00:02,940 --> 00:00:06,165
an HTML parser written in the Python programming language.

3
00:00:06,165 --> 00:00:09,000
Beautiful Soup makes it easy to parse, navigate,

4
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:11,865
and extract information from HTML documents.

5
00:00:11,865 --> 00:00:13,815
The name is derived from the Tag Soup,

6
00:00:13,815 --> 00:00:16,230
which refers to the unstructured and difficult to parse

7
00:00:16,230 --> 00:00:19,260
HTML found on a couple of websites.

8
00:00:19,260 --> 00:00:20,940
Let's take a look at how to use

9
00:00:20,940 --> 00:00:24,315
the Beautiful Soup library to extract data from an HTML file.

10
00:00:24,315 --> 00:00:27,060
Here I'm using our HTML page on the book,

11
00:00:27,060 --> 00:00:29,250
the language_of_flowers from archive.org

12
00:00:29,250 --> 00:00:32,790
downloaded as an HTML file that we'll use for this demo.

13
00:00:32,790 --> 00:00:36,110
I'm going to start by importing the Beautiful Soup library.

14
00:00:36,110 --> 00:00:41,515
I'll then try to open the language_of_flowers_html page as the file object fp,

15
00:00:41,515 --> 00:00:46,040
I'm then going to past this file object and the type of parser that I want to use,

16
00:00:46,040 --> 00:00:47,960
which in this case it's an HTML parser to

17
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:53,035
the Beautiful Soup constructor assigning the result to the flower_soup variable.

18
00:00:53,035 --> 00:00:57,890
Let's actually go ahead and look at Beautiful Soup's parsed output, flower_soup.

19
00:00:57,890 --> 00:01:02,570
Note that we have a large HTML file here filled with many tags.

20
00:01:02,570 --> 00:01:05,150
We'll be inspecting this in detail in a bit.

21
00:01:05,150 --> 00:01:07,790
I would like to make this output a bit cleaner though,

22
00:01:07,790 --> 00:01:10,070
by having a separate line for each tab.

23
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:14,990
Here what I can use is the pre-defined method that Beautiful Soup is offering that

24
00:01:14,990 --> 00:01:20,085
prints the format in Unicode string of the HTML just for viewing purposes.

25
00:01:20,085 --> 00:01:23,105
For example, although it's not obvious to see right away,

26
00:01:23,105 --> 00:01:26,000
notice how in the original version before using predefine,

27
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:30,695
the title tags and the content are really all smushed in one line.

28
00:01:30,695 --> 00:01:32,210
In the prettified version,

29
00:01:32,210 --> 00:01:36,575
the title tags and the content between them is actually separated on different lines,

30
00:01:36,575 --> 00:01:38,450
which makes it easier to understand what are

31
00:01:38,450 --> 00:01:41,590
these tag being used for and what's going on between the tag.

32
00:01:41,590 --> 00:01:43,820
Now, I could also switch over to

33
00:01:43,820 --> 00:01:47,470
my text editor for a better way of viewing the HTML if I wanted to.

34
00:01:47,470 --> 00:01:49,815
Let's now navigate the website.

35
00:01:49,815 --> 00:01:52,055
Looking at the HTML of the webpage,

36
00:01:52,055 --> 00:01:54,200
one of the first things that we may want to do is

37
00:01:54,200 --> 00:01:57,455
programmatically extract the title of the webpage.

38
00:01:57,455 --> 00:02:00,470
We can see that the title is neatly nestled within

39
00:02:00,470 --> 00:02:04,480
the title tags in the first few lines of the HTML file.

40
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:09,290
We can use Beautiful Soup's find method to iterate over tags and

41
00:02:09,290 --> 00:02:14,110
strings in the HTML document and find the first result where the title tag is used.

42
00:02:14,110 --> 00:02:17,555
Let's go ahead and do this right now by using.find on

43
00:02:17,555 --> 00:02:20,945
our flower_soup variable with the title text.

44
00:02:20,945 --> 00:02:23,330
Now let's go ahead and print the output and we're able to

45
00:02:23,330 --> 00:02:26,720
actually see the title along with the actual title tags.

46
00:02:26,720 --> 00:02:29,270
But what is I only want to see the content between

47
00:02:29,270 --> 00:02:32,555
the tags and not the actual HTML tags themselves?

48
00:02:32,555 --> 00:02:37,550
Here I can use.text on the outputs of the final result

49
00:02:37,550 --> 00:02:42,965
and then.strip to remove any leading and trailing spaces of the text.

50
00:02:42,965 --> 00:02:47,915
Now we can actually see the content of the title without the HTML tags.

51
00:02:47,915 --> 00:02:50,365
Let's try again on a different tag.

52
00:02:50,365 --> 00:02:54,695
Here I want to look at the username of the person who uploaded the book on archive.

53
00:02:54,695 --> 00:02:59,210
Now, there are multiple a tags that we're going to find as part of this HTML,

54
00:02:59,210 --> 00:03:03,100
where an a tag is actually defining a hyperlink.

55
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:07,220
Now, what I'm going to go ahead and do is specify the specific class of

56
00:03:07,220 --> 00:03:11,075
tag that I want to search for so that I can narrow down the results.

57
00:03:11,075 --> 00:03:14,015
Assuming that I've already identified this beforehand,

58
00:03:14,015 --> 00:03:18,515
I'm going to go ahead and specify to the find function my tag type as a

59
00:03:18,515 --> 00:03:23,735
and the class of this tag as class = item-upload-info_uploader-name.

60
00:03:23,735 --> 00:03:27,815
I've done just that here and provided it as input to the find function.

61
00:03:27,815 --> 00:03:31,210
Now, take a look at the results after using.text on the output,

62
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:36,220
we see hank_b is the username of the uploader of the book, which is correct.

63
00:03:36,220 --> 00:03:40,940
Let's look at an example of using one other function in Beautiful Soup, find all.

64
00:03:40,940 --> 00:03:44,380
What happens if we have multiple items that we want to retrieve at once?

65
00:03:44,380 --> 00:03:48,710
As an example, there are different collection items that this book is a part of.

66
00:03:48,710 --> 00:03:49,790
Here in our case,

67
00:03:49,790 --> 00:03:51,140
we actually have two;

68
00:03:51,140 --> 00:03:53,720
Cornell University Library and American Libraries.

69
00:03:53,720 --> 00:03:58,825
I want to get the texts nestled between the a tags with the class collection item.

70
00:03:58,825 --> 00:04:02,480
As you can see here, the Cornell University Library and American

71
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:06,590
Library is pretty neatly nestled within this big a tag.

72
00:04:06,590 --> 00:04:10,700
What I'm going to do is use Beautiful Soup to find all method specify

73
00:04:10,700 --> 00:04:15,035
the tag that I want to search for as an a and the class as collection item.

74
00:04:15,035 --> 00:04:17,135
Now what is this going to do is return

75
00:04:17,135 --> 00:04:19,670
all results in the HTML that match these conditions,

76
00:04:19,670 --> 00:04:21,620
assigning it to collection items.

77
00:04:21,620 --> 00:04:25,010
As we can see, collection items is output is a list.

78
00:04:25,010 --> 00:04:27,500
Let's actually iteratively print the items in

79
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:29,780
the list and we'll use.text on each of them.

80
00:04:29,780 --> 00:04:32,420
We can now see that we programmatically extracted

81
00:04:32,420 --> 00:04:36,490
the two collections that the book belongs to from the a tag.

82
00:04:36,490 --> 00:04:40,895
Now, if we want to use the.find function on the same use case,

83
00:04:40,895 --> 00:04:42,965
it will only return the first result,

84
00:04:42,965 --> 00:04:44,105
as we can see below,

85
00:04:44,105 --> 00:04:47,030
which is why we do need to use the find all function.

86
00:04:47,030 --> 00:04:50,390
A tool like Beautiful Soup is really useful for

87
00:04:50,390 --> 00:04:54,830
reproducible workflows when you may need to extract the same data in the future again,

88
00:04:54,830 --> 00:05:00,365
or if you need to use the same functions on HTML files with similar tags and structures.

89
00:05:00,365 --> 00:05:04,070
However, sometimes if you're performing a one-off analysis,

90
00:05:04,070 --> 00:05:06,995
you don't necessarily need to use Beautiful Soup.

91
00:05:06,995 --> 00:05:09,980
In some cases, you may just copy the data in your browser

92
00:05:09,980 --> 00:05:13,670
manually and just paste it into your data application, like Google Sheets.

93
00:05:13,670 --> 00:05:18,260
For certain applications, you can also use special functions to make this easier.

94
00:05:18,260 --> 00:05:20,330
For example, Google Sheets has

95
00:05:20,330 --> 00:05:24,880
an import HTML function that can pull a list or a table from the HTML page.

96
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:29,030
We'll be looking how to pull a table from a particular Wikipedia article looking at

97
00:05:29,030 --> 00:05:33,830
total fertility rate in India from the late 19th century to the earliest 20th century.

98
00:05:33,830 --> 00:05:36,380
You're wearing Google Sheets and we're going to go ahead and use

99
00:05:36,380 --> 00:05:39,815
the import HTML function, specifying the URL,

100
00:05:39,815 --> 00:05:41,600
the type of objects that we want to pull,

101
00:05:41,600 --> 00:05:44,390
which is a table actually that's on this Wikipedia page,

102
00:05:44,390 --> 00:05:45,780
and the index of the table.

103
00:05:45,780 --> 00:05:49,670
This particular table that we're trying to pull is the fourth table in the page.

104
00:05:49,670 --> 00:05:51,665
Going ahead and running the function,

105
00:05:51,665 --> 00:05:54,080
we can see after a couple of moments that it is

106
00:05:54,080 --> 00:05:58,440
successfully loading the data into Google Sheets for us.

